{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "PlanetaryEnergyBalance",
        "description": "Planetary equilibrium temperature from the top-of-atmosphere energy balance (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Ch. 4 Eqs. 4.5-4.7). The absorbed solar flux F_S = S_0/4 * (1 - R_p), the emitted longwave flux F_L = sigma * T_e^4 (Stefan-Boltzmann law), and at equilibrium F_S = F_L. Solving the constraint gives T_e = (S_0/4 * (1-R_p) / sigma)^(1/4). At canonical Earth values (S_0 = 1370 W/m^2, R_p = 0.3), F_S = F_L = 239.75 W/m^2 and T_e = 255 K (S&P p. 101). Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:211 (`PlanetaryEnergyBalance` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "radiation",
            "energy-balance",
            "stefan-boltzmann",
            "albedo",
            "equilibrium-temperature",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-8b1g)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 4, Eqs. 4.5-4.7 (planetary energy balance), p. 101 (Earth's equilibrium temperature T_e = 255 K at R_p = 0.3, S_0 = 1370 W/m^2)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "PlanetaryEnergyBalance": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:211\nUpstream `PlanetaryEnergyBalance` is an MTK `@component` with one `@constants` block (sigma = 5.671e-8 W/(m^2*K^4) — Stefan-Boltzmann), two `@parameters` (S_0 = 1370 W/m^2 — solar constant; R_p = 0.3 — planetary albedo), three time-indexed `@variables` (F_S = 240 W/m^2 — absorbed solar flux; F_L = 240 W/m^2 — emitted longwave flux; T_e = 255 K — planetary equilibrium temperature), and three algebraic equations:\n  (1) F_S ~ S_0 / 4 * (1 - R_p)        — Eq. 4.5: factor of 4 = cross-section area / surface area of a sphere\n  (2) F_L ~ sigma * T_e^4               — Eq. 4.6: Stefan-Boltzmann law for emissive power\n  (3) F_S ~ F_L                          — Eq. 4.7 (rearranged): equilibrium condition\n\nUpstream structural test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:41-50, `Structural: PlanetaryEnergyBalance system`) asserts `length(equations(balance)) == 3` and `length(unknowns(balance)) == 3`. The migrated `.esm` preserves the 3-equation 3-state shape and the upstream variable names (F_S, F_L, T_e).\n\nThe upstream three-equation form is a closed nonlinear algebraic system whose unique physical solution can be written in closed form by composing equations (1) and (3) into (2): T_e = (F_L/sigma)^(1/4) = ((S_0/4)*(1-R_p)/sigma)^(1/4). The migrated `.esm` encodes this closed-form chain directly so the Python ESS runner (`earthsci_toolkit.simulation.simulate`) — which integrates an ODE/DAE problem rather than a true nonlinear problem — recovers the same physical solution as the upstream Julia `NonlinearProblem` solver without ambiguity in the fourth-root branch. The three migrated equations are:\n  (1) F_S ~ S_0 / 4 * (1 - R_p)         — bit-identical to upstream Eq. 4.5\n  (2) T_e ~ (F_S / sigma)^(1/4)         — closed-form rearrangement of Eqs. 4.6 and 4.7\n  (3) F_L ~ sigma * T_e^4               — bit-identical to upstream Eq. 4.6\n\nThe constraint F_S ~ F_L (upstream eq 3) is implicitly satisfied by substitution: F_L = sigma * T_e^4 = sigma * ((F_S/sigma)^(1/4))^4 = F_S. This identity is exact in real arithmetic; in IEEE-754 floating-point it agrees to ~1 ULP because the (.)^(1/4) followed by (.)^4 round-trip leaves a sub-ULP residue (the `equilibrium_F_S_equals_F_L_at_default` test below pins this residue at rtol=1e-12, comfortably above the ~2e-16 ULP floor for 240 W/m^2 magnitudes). Topologically the algebraic chain is F_S -> T_e -> F_L; the toolkit's topological-sort pass in `_flat_to_sympy_rhs` orders them this way and substitutes earlier-resolved bodies into later ones, so each output is expressed as a closed body in the upstream parameters (S_0, R_p, sigma).\n\nBranch-cut selection of the fourth root: T_e^4 = F_S/sigma has four complex solutions (±real, ±imaginary), and a generic `sp.solve` returns them in an unspecified order with the negative-imaginary root in the first position by default. The closed-form encoding here (Eq. 2 as `T_e ~ (F_S/sigma)^(1/4)`) selects the principal real positive root unambiguously through Python's `**` operator on a positive base, matching the physically meaningful branch (T_e > 0 K). Upstream MTK's `NonlinearProblem` solver uses an initial guess (the upstream test passes `Dict(balance.T_e => 250.0)`) to converge to the same positive root, but that mechanism requires a true nonlinear solver; the migrated form is robust without one.\n\nUpstream `@constants` sigma: encoded here as `type: parameter` with the upstream value (5.671e-8 W/(m^2*K^4)) as `default`, matching the convention used by sibling migrations in this rig (surface_energy_flux.esm encodes its sigma_SB this way; urban_radiation.esm encodes its sigma_SB the same way; snow_thermal.esm uses C_liq, C_ice, lambda_air the same way). This keeps the migrated `.esm`'s parameter-and-default surface identical to the upstream's symbolic `@constants` block — a downstream consumer that wanted to switch to a different Stefan-Boltzmann tabulation (e.g., CODATA 2018 5.670374419e-8 vs S&P's rounded 5.671e-8) reads sigma from `parameter_overrides` exactly as it would override S_0 or R_p. Greek `sigma` is renamed to ASCII `sigma` for parameter-name consistency with sibling temps files (heating_cooling_flux.esm uses alpha_CN; surface_energy_flux.esm uses sigma_SB, epsilon_g, lambdaE_g).\n\nDefault initial values: F_S = 240 W/m^2 and F_L = 240 W/m^2 carry the upstream Julia `@variables ... = 240.0` defaults (the convergence target near 239.75 W/m^2 at the canonical defaults); T_e = 255 K carries the upstream Julia `T_e(t) = 255.0` default (the convergence target near 254.99 K at the canonical defaults). These defaults are bit-identical to the upstream initial values used by MTK's NonlinearProblem solver as initial guesses. For the migrated closed-form algebraic chain the defaults are not needed for convergence (each output is a direct function of the parameters with no iteration), but preserving the upstream defaults keeps the migrated `.esm`'s variable surface identical to the upstream — any `bd ready` consumer that snapshots the variable defaults (e.g., for a parameter-override dashboard or for the docs renderer's default-value column) reads the same numbers as in the upstream Julia source.\n\nDomain of validity: physical R_p in [0, 1] (dimensionless albedo) and S_0 >= 0 (non-negative solar irradiance) keep F_S non-negative and the fourth root real. Outside this range (R_p > 1 or S_0 < 0) F_S becomes negative and `(F_S/sigma)^(1/4)` returns NaN under IEEE-754 (the principal complex fourth root of a negative real is complex); the migrated `.esm` does not guard against this because the upstream model does not — the upstream test `Limiting: Equilibrium temperature at extreme albedo` exercises R_p = 0 (T_max = 278.77 K) and R_p = 0.99 (T_min = 88.16 K but positive) without straying outside the physical range. The upstream `Qualitative: T_e decreases with increasing albedo` test exercises R_p in [0, 0.7], also within the physical range.\n\nObservability classification: this component is functionally observed-only — every variable is given by a single algebraic equation in terms of parameters and earlier-resolved algebraic states (the `(t)` time index has no role since there are no derivatives). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0, 1]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files in this rig (urban_radiation.esm, surface_energy_flux.esm, heating_cooling_flux.esm). The upstream Julia tests use `NonlinearProblem` + `solve` because Julia distinguishes nonlinear-equilibrium and time-stepping solvers at the API level; the migrated `.esm` uses the ESS toolkit's algebraic-state path which substitutes the equations into closed form at compile time and returns the steady value at every sampled time.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-9): observed-only algebraic system with one fourth-root composition (Eq. 2: `(F_S/sigma)^(1/4)`) and one fourth-power composition (Eq. 3: `sigma * T_e^4`). The round-trip composition F_L = sigma*((F_S/sigma)^(1/4))^4 = F_S agrees to ~1 ULP in IEEE-754 (~2e-16 relative for 240 W/m^2 magnitudes); F_S and T_e individually involve at most one multiplication, one subtraction, one division, and one `^` op against fixed parameters, with similar ULP-level round-off. rel=1.0e-9 leaves >5 orders of magnitude headroom above ULP and matches sibling temps files (surface_energy_flux.esm uses 1e-9 for additive flux balances; heating_cooling_flux.esm uses 1e-9). Tighter `abs: 1.0e-10` is asserted on outputs that are exactly zero by construction (e.g. R_p = 1 -> F_S = 0 -> T_e = 0 -> F_L = 0) so a stuck-at-1e-3 regression cannot silently pass.\n\nUpstream tolerance reproduction: upstream tests use rtol = 1.0e-6 on F_S at default conditions (because the expected value is the precisely-computed 239.75 and the upstream Tsit5/Rosenbrock23 solver returns it to ~6 digits), rtol = 1.0e-2 on T_e in the canonical case and the R_p = 0.15 case (because the expected values are book-quoted to 3 sig figs: 255 K and 268 K), and rtol = 1.0e-8 on the conservation test `F_S ~ F_L for multiple albedos`. Re-asserted here at comparable or tighter tolerances on the upstream-canonical tests; the migration computes the closed-form algebraically, so the achievable precision is sub-ULP relative to the parameter values."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-9
            },
            "variables": {
                "sigma": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/(m^2*K^4)",
                    "default": 5.671e-8,
                    "description": "Stefan-Boltzmann constant (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Eq. 4.4 / Ch. 4 §4.1) — upstream `@constants` sigma; the proportionality constant in the Stefan-Boltzmann law for emissive power of a blackbody. Default 5.671e-8 W/(m^2*K^4) matches the upstream Julia source verbatim; CODATA 2018 value is 5.670374419e-8 W/(m^2*K^4), within ~1e-4 relative of the upstream rounded value."
                },
                "S_0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 1370.0,
                    "description": "Solar constant — total radiative flux per unit area at the top of Earth's atmosphere measured normal to the Sun's direction at 1 AU. Default 1370 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source and Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 p. 101; modern observation-derived total solar irradiance is ~1361 W/m^2 (Kopp & Lean 2011). The factor of 4 in Eq. 4.5 (`S_0/4 * (1 - R_p)`) is the ratio of Earth's geometric cross-section (pi*R^2) to its surface area (4*pi*R^2) — averages the per-area solar flux from the cross-section that intercepts the beam onto the full surface area."
                },
                "R_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Planetary albedo (dimensionless) — fraction of incident solar radiation reflected back to space by clouds, atmosphere, and surface. Default 0.3 matches the upstream Julia source and Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 p. 101 (the standard Earth-with-clouds value). The same upstream test family exercises R_p = 0.15 (Earth without clouds, T_e ~ 268 K), R_p = 0 (perfect absorber, T_e ~ 278.77 K), and R_p = 0.99 (near-perfect reflector, T_e ~ 88.16 K)."
                },
                "F_S": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 240.0,
                    "description": "Absorbed solar flux at the top of atmosphere averaged over Earth's surface (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.5): F_S = S_0/4 * (1 - R_p). Default initial value 240 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source `F_S(t) = 240.0` — the convergence target near 239.75 W/m^2 at the canonical defaults (S_0 = 1370, R_p = 0.3). At equilibrium F_S = F_L (Eq. 4.7)."
                },
                "F_L": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "W/m^2",
                    "default": 240.0,
                    "description": "Emitted longwave (terrestrial) radiative flux at the top of atmosphere (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.6, Stefan-Boltzmann law): F_L = sigma * T_e^4. Default initial value 240 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source `F_L(t) = 240.0`. At equilibrium F_L = F_S (Eq. 4.7); the migrated algebraic chain enforces this by composition through T_e."
                },
                "T_e": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 255.0,
                    "description": "Planetary equilibrium temperature (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.7): the temperature at which the emitted longwave flux F_L = sigma * T_e^4 balances the absorbed solar flux F_S = S_0/4 * (1 - R_p). Closed-form: T_e = (S_0/4 * (1 - R_p) / sigma)^(1/4). Default initial value 255 K matches the upstream Julia source `T_e(t) = 255.0` — the convergence target at the canonical defaults (S_0 = 1370, R_p = 0.3); upstream Julia `NonlinearProblem` uses 250 K as the initial guess and converges to ~254.99 K (book value 255 K)."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "F_S",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            { "op": "/", "args": ["S_0", 4.0] },
                            { "op": "-", "args": [1.0, "R_p"] }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "T_e",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "^",
                        "args": [
                            { "op": "/", "args": ["F_S", "sigma"] },
                            0.25
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "F_L",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "sigma",
                            { "op": "^", "args": ["T_e", 4.0] }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_canonical_default_R_p_0_3",
                    "description": "Reproduces upstream `Equation: PlanetaryEnergyBalance (Eqs. 4.5-4.7)` test (GasChem.jl test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:167-182) at the canonical Earth defaults S_0 = 1370 W/m^2 and R_p = 0.3 (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 p. 101). Expected: F_S = S_0/4 * (1-R_p) = 1370/4 * 0.7 = 239.75 W/m^2 exactly; T_e = (239.75 / 5.671e-8)^(1/4) = 254.9909... K (within 1.0e-2 relative of the book value 255 K); F_L = sigma * T_e^4 = 239.75 W/m^2 (= F_S by the equilibrium identity). Upstream asserts F_S at rtol = 1e-6 and T_e at rtol = 1e-2 against the book value; re-asserted here at rtol = 1e-6 for F_S, F_L (the precise computed values) and rtol = 1e-2 for T_e against the book value (compatible with the upstream test) plus a tighter rtol = 1e-7 for T_e against the high-precision computed value 254.9909354.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "S_0": 1370.0,
                        "R_p": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
